High-throughput screening platforms have allowed researchers to systematically screen a large number of genes associated with influenza virus infection in vitro, in animals or in humans. The availability of deep sequencing data of the human genome allows researchers to compare genetic variations between influenza patients and the general population [16•]. These technological advances, combined with in vitro or bioinformatics analysis, have revealed several genes associated with severe influenza (Figure 2
and Table 1
). In this review, we focus on specific host genes that have been shown to be directly related to the pathogenesis of human influenza identified or with updated knowledge in the past 2 years.
